text: Non-native parasitoids, released from 1895 to 1960 to control O. blackburni and O. accepta (pests on coconut palm and sugarcane respectively) (Funasaki et al. 1988) were implicated in the declines of several other Omiodes moths (Gagné and Christensen 1985). text: This species is threatened by direct mortality due to the presence of non-native invertebrate predators and parasitoids. Its habitat is also threatened due to host plant declines, casued in part due to competition from non-native grasses, which generally have higher growth rates, higher seed production, more efficient dispersal mechanisms and higher tolerance for disturbances, such as grazing by ungulates and fire (Ammondt et al. 2012).
